The paper deals with the computational power of distributed systems, specifically population protocols and their variants. This falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The paper also involves the analysis of algorithms and their complexity, which could fall under the sub-category of Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS). The use of graphs and networks in the analysis suggests the sub-category of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI). The paper also involves the study of logical systems and their expressiveness, which could fall under the sub-category of Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO). Finally, the paper involves the study of communication models, which could fall under the sub-category of Information Theory (cs.IT).
